<paragraph id="CE49824EFFD7FFC3FF09FAC2FC61164E" blockId="17.[151,916,1347,1408]" box="[151,916,1347,1373]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<heading id="95013522FFD7FFC3FF09FAC2FC61164E" bold="true" box="[151,916,1347,1373]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">
<emphasis id="FC825E5CFFD7FFC3FF09FAC2FC61164E" bold="true" box="[151,916,1347,1373]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName id="09F6F9CDFFD7FFC3FF09FAC2FD95164E" authority="Vanzolini, 1996" authorityName="Vanzolini" authorityYear="1996" box="[151,608,1347,1373]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Epictia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borapeliotes">
<emphasis id="FC825E5CFFD7FFC3FF09FAC2FE7D164E" bold="true" box="[151,392,1347,1373]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Epictia borapeliotes</emphasis>
(Vanzolini, 
<number id="783E9069FFD7FFC3FD82FAC2FDAD164E" box="[540,600,1347,1373]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
“Cobra-de-chumbinho”
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CE49824EFFD7FFC3FF09FAE6FE871693" blockId="17.[151,916,1347,1408]" box="[151,370,1383,1408]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">(Figs. 8.3 and 21.2)</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CE49824EFFD7FFC3FF09FA33FEE715E5" blockId="17.[151,1437,1458,1782]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Caatinga endemic species. Occurs in the states of Ceará, Rio Grande do Norte, Paraíba, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Bahia. Most records are from lowland areas from sea level to 
<quantity id="090E2FABFFD7FFC3FC60FA56FBBD16FC" box="[1022,1096,1495,1520]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="500.0">500 m</quantity>
maximum elevation, covered with open vegetation including bushy caatinga, arboreal caatinga, and herbaceous caatinga on sandy soils. It was also recently recorded in a Cerrado enclave in Mucugê, 
<taxonomicName id="09F6F9CDFFD7FFC3FC96F9A3FC131528" authority="Plateau" authorityName="Plateau" box="[776,998,1570,1595]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Podostemaceae" genus="Diamantina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Diamantina Plateau</taxonomicName>
, 
<quantity id="090E2FABFFD7FFC3FC6CF9A2FBCD1529" box="[1010,1080,1571,1595]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.379999999999999" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="938.0">938 m</quantity>
elevation (
<bibRefCitation id="AA67FFBFFFD7FFC3FB2AF9A3FA641528" author="Freitas" box="[1204,1425,1570,1595]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" refString="Freitas, M. A., Verissimo, D. &amp; Uhlig, V. (2012 a) Squamate reptiles of the central Chapada Diamantina, with focus on the municipality of Mucuge, State of Bahia, Brazil. Check List, 8, 16 - 22." type="journal article" year="2012" yearSuffix="a">
Freitas 
<emphasis id="FC825E5CFFD7FFC3FA96F9A5FACD1528" box="[1288,1336,1570,1595]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number id="783E9069FFD7FFC3FAD9F9A2FA711528" box="[1351,1412,1571,1595]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2012.0">2012</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
). Five records of this species were also observed near the coast (
<collectionCode id="A8E71A8BFFD7FFC3FCE8F9C9FC451573" box="[886,944,1608,1632]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/t9x4-866k" name="Tsukuba Botanical Garden" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">TBG</collectionCode>
pers. obs.) in municipalities of 
<collectingCountry id="B6E1C2DEFFD7FFC3FABAF9C6FA941573" box="[1316,1377,1607,1632]" name="South Africa" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Natal</collectingCountry>
(Rio Grande do Norte State) and João Pessoa (Paraíba State). Apparently, it has a wide tolerance to variations in humidity levels, which allows its occurrence both in semi arid Caatinga and near wetter coastal areas (
<bibRefCitation id="AA67FFBFFFD7FFC3FAB1F913FF1415C3" author="Vanzolini" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. (1996 b) A new (and very old) species of Leptotyphlops from northeastern Brazil (Serpentes, Leptotyphlopidae). Papeis Avulsos Zoologia, 39, 281 - 291." type="journal article" year="1996" yearSuffix="b">
Vanzolini 
<number id="783E9069FFD7FFC3FF09F936FF2615C3" box="[151,211,1719,1744]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1996.0">1996</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
). It has fossorial habits, is nocturnal and diurnal, and feeds mostly on arthropods (
<bibRefCitation id="AA67FFBFFFD7FFC3FB08F936FEF015E5" author="Vanzolini" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. (1996 b) A new (and very old) species of Leptotyphlops from northeastern Brazil (Serpentes, Leptotyphlopidae). Papeis Avulsos Zoologia, 39, 281 - 291." type="journal article" year="1996" yearSuffix="b">
Vanzolini 
<number id="783E9069FFD7FFC3FA93F936FABD15C3" box="[1293,1352,1719,1744]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1996.0">1996</number>
b; 
<collectionCode id="A8E71A8BFFD7FFC3FAFAF939FA6915C3" box="[1380,1436,1720,1744]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/t9x4-866k" name="Tsukuba Botanical Garden" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">TBG</collectionCode>
pers. obs.
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
